column7: American Woodcock;  nest situation on the ground at the foot of a small thornbush.Level place on hillside of Mordey's Hollow Valley.  Place slightly overgrown with bushes & small trees.  A few dead leaves & some dry grass line the shallow hollow in which the eggs were deposited.  "When I first found the nest, there were but two eggs.  I took them & substituted two stones.  Came back in an hour or so &  found she had laid the third egg in my absence.  June 3 she was sitting but no more eggs.  Had left the nest & stones on the 4th." Incubation: fresh  Identity: positive, saw bird several times  Bradbury got set from R S Wheeler April 1914  CMNH #421; Coll: Doolittle  E A
